{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496628"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:52:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:52:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1397"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1397"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.79,0.01,0.16,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101498"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1397"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83937"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"402"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1328"},{"type":"tags","id":"3051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3507"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42303"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101498"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-day history of steadily worsening breathlessness. He reports shortness of breath when walking several blocks or walking upstairs and can no longer manage the latter. He also reports recurrent palpitations and a feeling of pressure in the chest for the past five months. He does not smoke. He has a 30-year history of drinking at least seven beers each day. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is alert and orientated. His pulse rate is 110 beats/min, respiratory rate 22 breaths/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, SpO2 92% on room air and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His jugular venous pressure is 9 cm above the sternal angle at 45\u00b0, and bilateral crackles are auscultated at both lung bases. Cardiac examination reveals an S3 gallop and a displaced apex beat. There is pitting oedema bilaterally to his upper shins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate approach to management of the underlying problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abstinence from alcohol","Dietary iron restriction","Thiamine infusion","Prednisolone","Levothyroxine"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of dilated cardiomyopathy, most likely caused by his chronic alcohol use. \u003Cstrong\u003EAbstinence from alcohol\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate approach to management of the underlying problem. Chronic alcohol consumption is a well-established cause of secondary non-ischaemic dilated cardiomyopathy. Both ethanol and its metabolite acetaldehyde are toxic to cardiac myocytes, leading to ventricular dilation and reduced contractility. If detected early, consistent abstinence from alcohol can lead to improvement or even reversal of cardiomyopathy. Given the high likelihood of significant alcohol dependence, a multidisciplinary approach including withdrawal management and psychosocial support is essential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDietary iron restriction\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in haemochromatosis, which can also cause dilated cardiomyopathy, but there are no features in this case to suggest iron overload such as hepatomegaly, hyperpigmentation, or arthralgia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThiamine infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat wet beriberi, a condition caused by thiamine deficiency that can also result in cardiomyopathy. While this patient is at risk of thiamine deficiency due to chronic alcohol use, the clinical picture is more consistent with alcohol-induced cardiomyopathy rather than beriberi, especially in the absence of peripheral neuropathy or confusion. Thiamine would be indicated acutely in this patient due to his high alcohol intake and risk of thiamine deficiency, but this is not a long-term management solution for dilated cardiomyopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is used in the management of cardiac sarcoidosis, which can cause dilated cardiomyopathy, but there is no history or clinical evidence of sarcoidosis in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELevothyroxine\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for hypothyroidism, which can rarely cause dilated cardiomyopathy, but this patient does not have symptoms or signs suggestive of hypothyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic alcohol use is a significant and reversible cause of dilated cardiomyopathy.","Abstinence from alcohol can lead to improvement or reversal of alcohol-induced cardiomyopathy if instituted early.","Management of alcohol use disorder requires a multidisciplinary approach, including withdrawal management and psychosocial support."],"references":["Maisch B. Alcoholic cardiomyopathy : The result of dosage and individual predisposition. Herz. 2016 Sep;41(6):484-93. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27582365/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83937"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1397"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83937"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T11:16:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T11:53:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1397"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101498"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student 